From 9fca5f9cc582a66b54af8b8b962300e13b3a8178 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Kol Crooks <kol.crooks@datadoghq.com>
Date: Fri, 8 May 2026 14:48:01 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] Phase 10 Batch 4 follow-up: inline Move-to-Automation toggle,
 drop commands
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Replace the `KRT: Add/Remove Bot User…` command-palette entries with
an inline toggle on every comment header. Each comment's head row now
ends with a small button — `Move to Automation` for non-bots, `Move
to Discussion` for already-bots — that flips the author's bot status
for the active workspace. The button stays hidden until the user hovers
the comment (or focuses the button via keyboard) so the timeline
doesn't read busy, except when the comment IS already a bot, in which
case the button stays lit in the accent colour to make the current
state legible at a glance.

Reasoning: the bot list is something you classify when you see a
comment that's clearly automation. Forcing the user to discover and
type a command name to do that is the wrong shape. The command
palette in particular is invisible to non-power-users, so we keep it
free of KRT entries when an in-context UI surface exists.

The toggle is gated on a workspace existing for the PR's `(owner, repo)`;
without one there's no scope for the bot list and the button doesn't
render.
